item.title: Pakistan Plans Criminal Charges Against Pilots With Bogus Credentials
item.description: Pakistan said it would criminally charge pilots found to have obtained fraudulent flying credentials as the authorities raced to identify those who work for overseas airlines.

item.title: Russian Fighters Help Tighten Rebel Control of Libya's Largest Oil Field
item.description: Mercenaries connected to the Russian government have joined forces with a rebel militia to hold Libya’s largest oil field, European and Libyan officials said, prompting U.S. protests over foreign interference in the country’s most strategic industry.

item.title: China Message to U.S.: Crossing 'Red Lines' Could Put Trade Deal at Risk
item.description: Beijing has begun quietly delivering a message to Washington: U.S. pressure over matters China considers off limits could jeopardize Chinese purchases of farm goods and other U.S. exports under the “Phase One” trade deal.

item.title: Mexico City Security Chief Wounded in Assassination Attempt
item.description: Heavily armed gunmen opened fire on Mexico City’s security chief along the city’s most famous boulevard, in a failed assassination attempt the official blamed on the country’s most powerful criminal organization.

item.title: Venezuelan Opposition Guru Led Planning to Topple Maduro
item.description: The politically influential mentor of U.S.-backed Venezuelan opposition leader Juan Guaidó was behind a monthslong effort to contract mercenaries to overthrow President Nicolás Maduro, according to several people involved in the planning.

item.title: Trump's Planned Troop Withdrawal From Germany Leaves Berlin Cold
item.description: President Trump framed the U.S.’s decision to pull out 9,500 troops from Germany as punishment for Berlin’s low military spending. So far, Germany is unimpressed.
